<br>
Except for a few launches a year, the whole US space industry IS private. NASA provides rental of its launch facilities, if the company wishes to use them, but the rockets, the payloads, and the money is private.<br>
<br>
The military also does a number of launches<br>
<br>
Also, with the exception of the shuttle, the boosters (if US made) used by NASA and the military are variants of private missiles.<br>
<br>
Even the shuttle, ISS, and the bulk of payloads are privately manufactured.<br>
<br>
If NASA got completely out of the business the money would just go to tax cuts or other spending, or deficit reduction.<br>
They have little to to with what the real action is.<br>
<br>
Space has gone pretty much nowhere because it is expensive, unreliable, and provides minimum benefits.<br>
<br>
Most market niches - comm satellites, geo-observation, etc, are essentially filled.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
